[These reports are the second and third in recent months that describe
citrus HLB. I note that there are 2 spellings for the disease in the
literature; huanglongbing and huanglongbin (phonetically: wung-long-bing).
Can any of our readers provide an explanation for these different
spellings? There has also been some confusion over the nomenclature of the
causal organism. The correct spellings are: _Liberibacter asiaticus_ (for
the Asian form) and _Liberibacter africanus_ (for the African form).
There is no cure for the disease at present. More than 20 plant diseases
are associated with or known to be caused by bacteria-like organisms
(BLOs), which range in size from 0.25 to 0.5 by 0.8 to 4.0 micrometers. HLB
has been reported in Australasia (Northern Territory [Australia], Papua New
Guinea, East Timor) and in South Africa. A similar disease (cucurbit
yellow vine disease) has been reported to infect canteloupe, pumpkin,
squash and watermelon in USA (Oklahoma, Texas, Tennessee &
Massachusetts). - Mod.DH]
